Remaining types include blocks ($1.7 times 10^6$, 0.8%), thread reply controls, profile updates, list memberships, and other moderation records — 16 lexicon collections in total. The `records` schema includes `subject_uri`, `subject_did`, and a full `record_json` payload, enabling reconstruction of the target of every like, repost, follow, and block. A full description of the database table schema can be found in @apx-database.

Between the two different tables, there are a total of $3.09 times 10^6$ DIDs (direct ID) which are distinct users in all data set. Approximately 1.63 million users (52.8%) appear in `records` but never authored a post, therefore will be excluded from certain metrics as not active enough.

A systematic EDA was conducted to understand the distribution of user activity and identify which users drive the inter-event gap distribution, that is, the distribution of time that happens between actions. This magnitude is fundamental, as is what is going to drive the methodology of how to define how a session in should be found in the data (see Calibration @sec-cal-sessions). 

=== Event-Count distribution

The number of events per user follows a heavy-tailed power-law distribution. The median user has 8 events over the 8-day window; $P_75$ is 39 events; $P_99$ reaches 1,185 events. The top 1% produce 148 more events than the median user.

#figure(
  image("images/data/6-1_events_powerlaw.png", width: 100%),
  caption: flex-caption(
    [Complementary CDF of events per user (log-log).],
    [Complementary CDF of events per user (log-log). A power-law fit (Clauset et al. MLE with KS-based $x_min$ selection) yields $alpha approx 1.56$, $x_min = 8$. The straight-line decay in the tail confirms power-law behaviour.],
  )
) <fig-events-powerlaw>

A power-law fit via MLE with KS-based $x_min$ estimation @clauset2009powerlaw yields $alpha approx 1.56$, $x_min = 8$ events. Since the heavy tail begins at 8 events, users with fewer than 8 events — half of the population — are considered tourists whose activity is too sparse to produce meaningful session statistics.

The next step, once know the power-law of the events per user per 8 days, is to classify the users according to event counts. The @tbl-coverage shows the bins used to classify the users by total event count and asks: which stratum holds the most amount of events and gaps between them?

