The tourist majority ($<=5$ events, 52.7% of users) is barely visible in the gap distribution. The 501+ bucket adds another 27.7% of gaps, but users in this range generate over 62 events per day on average — a rate suspicious of automated or scheduled accounts. Together, just 6.3% of users drive 65.1% of the gap distribution.

On the basis of this EDA, two event tables were created in `data`, both time-windowed to the 8-day snapshot (April 11--18, 2026):

- *`data.all_events`* ($approx 1.6 times 10^6$ users, $>= 8$ events): all 6 major event types (likes, reposts, follows, blocks, top-level posts, replies). The $>= 8$ cutoff is the power-law $x_min$ from the all-events distribution ($alpha = 1.56$). This table feeds the browsing-oriented session pipeline.
- *`data.engaged_events`* ($approx 2.4 times 10^6$ users, $>= 4$ events): 5 engaged event types — reposts, follows, blocks, posts, replies — *without likes*. The $>= 4$ cutoff is the power-law $x_min$ for engaged events ($alpha = 1.67$). This table feeds the content-creation-oriented session pipeline and the inter-post gap analysis.

Both tables follow the schema `(did, time_us, event_type)`, with 32 hash-distributed buckets for parallel query execution. See @apx-database for the full database specification.

== Post Lifetime Analysis
<sec-data-lifetime>

Whereas session analysis is needed for the calibration, we will compute the quantities of interest of the simulation, to compare them with the data real life simulation data. This section studies the lifetime of $15.3 times 10^6$ top-level posts in the firehose snapshot (posts with `reply_root_uri IS NULL`).

=== Data Preparation

Two tables were created to support the analysis:

- *`data.post_lifetime`* — one row per top-level post, precomputing the first and last timestamp of each engagement type (repost, like, reply) plus total counts ($15.3 times 10^6$ rows).
- *`data.post_engagement_events`* — individual event timeline for every post, with columns `(post_did, post_rkey, event_time_us, event_type, actor_did)`. Enables temporal decay and cascade analysis ($approx 140 times 10^6$ rows).

Only top-level posts are included; replies are thread participants rather than original content. Quote-posts are absent from the dump (see @sec-data-firehose).

=== Engagement Counts

A striking 50.7% of posts receive no engagement at all. Of engaged posts, likes are the most common (92.7%), followed by replies (35.4%) and reposts (33.1%). The Python script `eda/fit_powerlaw_counts.py` fits a discrete power-law via MLE with KS-based $x_min$ selection and compares against lognormal, Weibull, and exponential alternatives via Vuong's LLR test.

For each engagement type, the counts in the tail follow a discrete power-law (@tbl-powerlaw-counts). The power-law is strongly favoured over all alternatives: Vuong's $R$ values range from $+2,933$ (replies vs lognormal) to $+85,822$ (combined vs exponential), with $p < 0.001$ throughout.

